## 3. Multiple Linear Regression

With $p$ predictors:

$$\hat{y} = \beta_0 + \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j x_j$$

### Interpretation of Coefficients

- $\beta_j$ represents the **expected change in $y$** for a **one-unit increase in $x_j$**, holding all other predictors constant.
- The intercept $\beta_0$ is the predicted value of $y$ when **all** $x_j = 0$.

---

## 4. The Matrix Formulation

Stack $n$ observations into matrix form:

$$\mathbf{y} = \mathbf{X} \boldsymbol{\beta} + \boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$$

Where:

$$\mathbf{X} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & x_{11} & x_{12} & \cdots & x_{1p} \\ 1 & x_{21} & x_{22} & \cdots & x_{2p} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ 1 & x_{n1} & x_{n2} & \cdots & x_{np} \end{bmatrix}, \quad \boldsymbol{\beta} = \begin{bmatrix} \beta_0 \\ \beta_1 \\ \vdots \\ \beta_p \end{bmatrix}, \quad \mathbf{y} = \begin{bmatrix} y_1 \\ y_2 \\ \vdots \\ y_n \end{bmatrix}$$

- $\mathbf{X}$ is the **design matrix** of shape $(n \times (p+1))$
- The leading column of ones encodes the intercept $\beta_0$

---

## 5. Ordinary Least Squares (OLS)

### Loss Function

OLS minimises the **Residual Sum of Squares (RSS)**:

$$\text{RSS}(\boldsymbol{\beta}) = \|\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta}\|^2 = \sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2$$

### Normal Equations

Setting $\nabla_{\boldsymbol{\beta}} \text{RSS} = 0$:

$$\mathbf{X}^\top \mathbf{X} \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} = \mathbf{X}^\top \mathbf{y}$$

Solving (when $\mathbf{X}^\top \mathbf{X}$ is invertible):

$$\boxed{\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} = (\mathbf{X}^\top \mathbf{X})^{-1} \mathbf{X}^\top \mathbf{y}}$$

### Hat Matrix (Projection)

The fitted values can be written as:

$$\hat{\mathbf{y}} = \mathbf{X}\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} = \underbrace{\mathbf{X}(\mathbf{X}^\top \mathbf{X})^{-1}\mathbf{X}^\top}_{\mathbf{H}} \mathbf{y}$$

$\mathbf{H}$ is the **hat matrix** or **projection matrix** — it projects $\mathbf{y}$ onto the column space of $\mathbf{X}$.

Properties of $\mathbf{H}$:
- Symmetric: $\mathbf{H}^\top = \mathbf{H}$
- Idempotent: $\mathbf{H}^2 = \mathbf{H}$

### Gauss–Markov Theorem

> Under the classical assumptions (zero-mean errors, homoscedasticity, no autocorrelation), the OLS estimator $\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}$ is the **Best Linear Unbiased Estimator (BLUE)**.

$$\text{Var}(\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}) = \sigma^2 (\mathbf{X}^\top \mathbf{X})^{-1}$$

---

## 6. Assumptions of Linear Models

| # | Assumption | Formal Statement |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | **Linearity** | $\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{y} \mid \mathbf{X}] = \mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta}$ |
| 2 | **No perfect multicollinearity** | $\text{rank}(\mathbf{X}) = p + 1$ |
| 3 | **Zero-mean errors** | $\mathbb{E}[\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}] = \mathbf{0}$ |
| 4 | **Homoscedasticity** | $\text{Var}(\varepsilon_i) = \sigma^2 \; \forall i$ |
| 5 | **No autocorrelation** | $\text{Cov}(\varepsilon_i, \varepsilon_j) = 0 \; \forall i \neq j$ |
| 6 | **Normality of errors** | $\varepsilon \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma^2)$ *(for inference)* |

